I think it's time to retire this Livejournal. It's been a good four years between Xanga and LJ, hahaha. Farewell.

William and Mary, Class of 2010 :-D

FREEEEEDOM (for 4 days).

Annnd man...sometime super soon :-o

Quote of the day: "I HATE SODA! AND I DON'T EVEN DRINK IT!"

Today reminded me of what it feels like to be genuinely happy :-)

One million tests later, I have come out alive. We've made it to the end of the first marking period. Now to repeat three more times :-)

Haha, yeah, but seriously. I am ecstatic for these two days off and for being done with grades for this marking period. When the bell rang today, I felt like I normally do before winter break. Good lord.

Let's relax and enjoy these days while we have 'em!
Excuse me, can we please graduate?
I have officially applied to college. My life is in the hands of the gods at this point. :-O
"This was one score that, really, everyone should have seen coming." - WW-P Today

Good and bad day. Mostly good though.

Remi and my superlative picture was totally awesome. I'm excited.

I was in a weirdly good mood for most of the day...until some stuff happened...but it'll be okay, I think.

I finally recorded the clarinet piece I'm sending to college...it went well, I believe.

The North-South game was AWESOME. I love our school...we have so much spirit it is absolutely ridiculous. 47-0, fools! WHOSE SOCKS ARE THESE?!? NORTH SOCKS!

After the game was fun too...went to Friday's for my first meal in like...11 hours, haha. The company wasn't so bad either, ;-).

Busy weekend homework-wise though..unfortunately. Nice end to a bad week though.

5 Odd Habits

1. Every time I come back to the computer after having walked away, I always recheck my email.

2. I must have at least one piece of gum per class period. It's become an addiction.

3. When I sign online, I have to read everyone's away message. HAVE TO.

4. Whenever I come upstairs from my basement, I run up the stairs in case there is anything/anyone scary down there.

5. When I'm bored, I type people's names that I know into a search engine and see what comes up.

You know, I keep telling myself and telling myself that I can't wait for graduation day to come. I've always felt that I couldn't wait to get out of this school and out of this town and away from the high school life forever and move forward. Nevertheless, it's on weeks like this one where I feel so sad thinking that I will have to leave all of this behind in nine months. Homecoming week - spirit week, the decorating, the pep rally, the football game - is one of my favorite weeks out of the year. I always just feel like our entire class comes together, especially with the decorating...and last night, that happened more than ever before. I suddenly felt so close to everyone in our class and as I was driving home last night, I realized that I don't know if I'm ready to leave just yet. Other times come up and I'm sure I will again feel as though I just want it all to be over...but right now, I just want to hold onto everything little by little. I love these people....I love the Class of 2006. We're awesome. We may not have officially won hall decorations, but we know that ours was the best anyway. It's so sad thinking that we'll never get to decorate again...I won't ever spend hours after school all week again...or get stressed beyond belief while decorating, only to have it all come together in the last half hour...we won't ever go to another pep rally and scream and cheer so loud for our class...

So begins our year of "last's." I think I'm finally beginning to comprehend what every senior has told me about their own last year of high school - that everyone becomes so close and you end up not wanting to leave right away.

"I can't remember all the times I tried to tell myself to hold onto these moments as they pass"

CLASS OF 2006 FOREVER!
This will, by far, be one of the craziest weeks of my entire life. Wish me luck. It'll be a miracle to survive.

We stumble in a tangled web,
decaying friendships almost dead
And hide behind a mask of lies
We twist and turn and we avoid,
all hope of salvage now devoid
I see the truth inside your eyes

You could resurrect a thousand words to deceive me more and more
A thousand words will give the reasons why I don't need you anymore

Time manipulates your heart,
preconception torn apart
Begin to doubt my state of mind
But I won't go down on what I said
I won't retract convictions read
I may perplex, but I'm not blind...

I have gone through quite a range of emotions in the past four hours. First, I was just excited to be a senior. Then...I was in utter disbelief...and now, I kind of feel like crying and I don't know why. This is just crazy...and talking to people and reading people's away messages I'm getting the feeling that everyone else is just as weirded out as I am.

How can we be seniors?!? We were just freshmen!

Going to bed in a few...getting ready for my last first day of school ever.

Not only was today one of the best days I have had in a long time, but it was also the absolute perfect end to my "last summer as an adolescent" (hah Jess!). 

So long sweet summer...

In other news, thanks to the wonderful Arati I am now guaranteed a parking space because I am going to drive her! Wooooo! That takes a whole load of stress off of my chest, haha.

Well, it's been good kids. Time to go back to our wall-less, window-less, South. As SENIORS.

And now for my annual end-of-summer quote:

"Every summer has a song, to remind me of the good times that passed. If only they could last forever..."

I just got home from graduation...it was really nice..very sad. It was sad that they're all leaving...and it also made me think about when I'm graduating. I mean, yeah, it's 3 years which is a while...but it also isn't. Middle school was 3 years...and think how fast that went by...and this year went so fast...so who's to say that next three won't either. I don't want to leave...I just want things to stay like this forever...but I know everyone has to grow up sometime. I just don't want to. 


I still can't believe we'rea ctually seniors.

Really really good day. Incredibly exhausting but good. Car wash from 9-5 - thanks to everyone who helped us out....definitely some funny times there, the foremost being Chris driving the stick shift car with the emergency break on and a noise as awful as the screeching of 4289237419 rats in a tiny space. Hahahah. Makes me laugh just remembering. Then tonight I hung out at Jen's pool with a lot of awesome people and good times were had by all. Honestly the best day I've had in a long time....

I found this from an old entry over a year ago. I thought it was interesting and I'd repost.

In LA today we spent a long time discussing the illusion of the green light in the novel The Great Gatsby by F. Scott Fitzgerald...and we discussed Gatsby's belief that one can, in fact, live in the past and, in essence, make things exactly the same as they used to be as if no time has passed. I don't agree...there is no way that anyone could get anywhere in life if they refuse to accept reality and move ahead, rather than backwards. However, I do wish sometimes that it were possible to redo events of the past or relive it or whatnot...it'd make change a whole lot less unnecessary. Wishful thinking, I suppose.
I guess it's sort of a good thing that reality is really setting in...it'll help me to accept things, I guess. It's the initial BANG...that moment when all of a sudden, things seem real. It's almost like someone comes up to you and slaps in the face, waking you up from the fantasy world you were trying to hold onto. And then comes the burn...the stinging raw feeling you're left with after the inital slap...and that's when the pain comes. The pain doesn't set in until right away, you know? It takes some time. That is exactly how I feel...I knew things were changing for a while now and I was slapped a while ago...it's just...the burning sensation hasn't set in until right now. And it hurts. A lot.
"Gatsby believed in the green light, the orgastic future that year by year recedes before us. It eluded us then, but that's no matter - tomorrow we will run faster, stretch out our arms farther....And one find morning -    So we beat on, boats against the current, borne back ceaselessly into the past." - The Great Gatsby
